WEBVTT

00:00.258 --> 00:01.259
My name is Brian Vassil.

00:01.279 --> 00:02.061
I'm one of your pastors.

00:02.101 --> 00:03.082
I'm excited that you're here.

00:03.402 --> 00:05.125
Here in the States, it is a holiday weekend.

00:05.145 --> 00:05.926
So kudos to you.

00:06.347 --> 00:06.787
You came out.

00:06.807 --> 00:10.412
I want to welcome all of our campuses as well online and all over the world.

00:10.472 --> 00:13.457
Thanks for being here and wrapping up our panic room series.

00:13.477 --> 00:14.598
You enjoyed the series so far?

00:15.219 --> 00:15.780
It's been great.

00:16.120 --> 00:21.388
And it's my hope today with every bit of me to be able to give you something that you didn't have when you came in.

00:21.608 --> 00:28.658
So I want to invite you to take out those notes you received when you came in and take some, write some stuff down that will help you, I believe, with what's coming.

00:28.962 --> 00:29.503
in your life.

00:29.543 --> 00:33.707
Let me take a quick, let me ask you around the room, how many of you do not like to be alone?

00:33.808 --> 00:34.348
Raise your hand.

00:34.368 --> 00:34.949
You don't like it.

00:35.790 --> 00:37.011
You just don't like being alone.

00:37.071 --> 00:38.213
My wife is that way.

00:38.993 --> 00:41.837
If she goes on an errand, she wants to get in the car, guess who's going with her?

00:42.738 --> 00:44.240
Me or the dog, one or the other.

00:44.320 --> 00:46.402
We have a little tiny dog that rides along with her.

00:46.802 --> 00:50.126
If she wants to go into a room and watch TV, she'd like to have me around there.

00:50.166 --> 00:50.967
And I mean, who can blame her?

00:50.987 --> 00:51.668
I mean, look at me.

00:52.749 --> 00:56.914
I mean, you know, who would want to be around a pastor 24-7, you know?

00:57.058 --> 01:02.705
Seriously, this is, I'm jackpot for her, but that's terribly arrogant.

01:03.867 --> 01:06.250
She just doesn't like to be alone, but she's not lonely.

01:07.291 --> 01:08.192
My wife is not lonely.

01:08.212 --> 01:12.598
There's a difference between being alone and being lonely, isn't there?

01:13.459 --> 01:15.001
I mean, we wrestle with this.

01:15.061 --> 01:18.866
Loneliness is that feeling that you have so much to say, but nobody to say it to.

01:20.098 --> 01:29.170
Loneliness is the feeling you have when you feel rejected, or the world has turned its back on you, or things just don't seem to be going right, and you're the only one enduring it.

01:29.951 --> 01:31.273
That's what we're gonna talk about today.

01:32.555 --> 01:33.195
Loneliness.

01:34.357 --> 01:37.782
How do we deal with the loneliness that we find ourselves in?

01:38.222 --> 01:39.444
It contributes to so much.

01:40.906 --> 01:46.413
Depression, obesity, insomnia, all these things that loneliness affects.

01:46.433 --> 01:50.098
In fact, I have a quote in my notes, it's from the US Surgeon General,

01:50.530 --> 01:51.231
or the former U.S.

01:51.291 --> 01:53.856
Surgeon General, Vivek, I think I'm saying his name, right?

01:53.876 --> 01:59.546
Vivek Murthy, who says this, cancer and obesity aren't the country's biggest health issues.

01:59.566 --> 02:02.131
It's loneliness and isolation.

02:02.151 --> 02:03.974
But how is that the case?

02:03.994 --> 02:06.679
I mean, after all, we carry a smartphone.

02:07.661 --> 02:11.067
How can we possibly be lonely when we have the world in our pocket?

02:11.087 --> 02:14.994
I would say that the smartphone contributes to loneliness.

02:16.290 --> 02:20.578
Because yeah, we're better connected with text, but text doesn't replace a real conversation, does it?

02:21.921 --> 02:25.908
I mean, a phone calls great, but isn't it nice to be in someone's home and get to know them one-on-one?

02:27.431 --> 02:30.076
But we hide behind social media.

02:30.737 --> 02:31.639
Everything's okay.

02:31.659 --> 02:32.481
I'm not lonely.

02:32.501 --> 02:34.925
And we post our best pictures to Instagram.

02:36.448 --> 02:39.634
Loneliness is something a lot of us deal with.

02:40.130 --> 02:41.973
I mean, why do we hurt so bad when we're lonely?

02:42.113 --> 02:43.915
I put this in your notes, please fill this in.

02:44.336 --> 02:48.061
I believe it's because we are designed by God to do life together.

02:48.161 --> 02:48.862
Would you agree with that?

02:49.663 --> 02:51.205
Genesis 2, 18, let's read it.

02:51.465 --> 02:55.831
It says, the Lord God said, it is not good for man to be alone.

02:55.871 --> 02:56.773
Now, remember what happened.

02:56.813 --> 02:57.734
God made everything.

02:58.856 --> 03:00.277
And he said what when he was finished?

03:00.618 --> 03:02.521
It is good.

03:04.263 --> 03:06.546
This is the first thing he said was not good.

03:08.002 --> 03:09.684
It's not good for man to be alone.

03:09.724 --> 03:11.767
It's not good for you to be apart from other people.

03:13.509 --> 03:14.891
Loneliness is not good.

03:15.932 --> 03:17.174
Pastor Troy says it all the time.

03:17.214 --> 03:19.096
One is too small of a number for greatness.

03:20.778 --> 03:21.359
I believe that.

03:22.501 --> 03:25.004
We are designed to do life with others.

03:25.885 --> 03:27.267
In fact, Mother Teresa says this.

03:27.387 --> 03:32.914
She says, the most terrible poverty is loneliness and the feeling of being unloved.

03:34.818 --> 03:35.419
doesn't it?

03:35.619 --> 03:38.622
Now I want you, let's before we go any further, I want to make sure we're clear on this.

03:39.023 --> 03:41.826
Loneliness does not mean there are nobody, there's nobody around you.

03:43.128 --> 03:45.991
You can be lonely in a crowd, can't you?

03:47.933 --> 03:52.679
Some of us are living with a spouse and every morning we wake up and roll over and look at them and feel like roommates.

03:54.922 --> 03:57.665
Not husband and wife.

03:57.685 --> 03:58.706
And we feel lonely.

03:59.490 --> 04:00.311
We're around friends.

04:00.371 --> 04:04.779
We're the only ones with the values that we have and we feel lonely in a crowd of people.

04:04.859 --> 04:11.330
Physical proximity has nothing to do with loneliness because some of us have been lonely a long time and we've hidden it really well.

04:13.012 --> 04:17.921
We smile and we cover it up and the devil just twists the knife in our back, doesn't he?

04:18.562 --> 04:20.906
He tries to convince you to hear the only one that feels like that.

04:22.408 --> 04:23.570
You had this coming.

04:24.546 --> 04:25.767
You did this to yourself.

04:26.748 --> 04:32.555
He'll tell you all the biggest lie of all is that you're the only one feeling like this, because I can tell you statistically you're not.

04:32.875 --> 04:33.956
In fact, fill these in if you would.

04:34.156 --> 04:37.120
The average person spends 80% of their time with other people.

04:37.160 --> 04:37.620
Did you know that?

04:37.640 --> 04:41.084
80% of our day is made up by spending it with somebody else.

04:41.825 --> 04:42.886
But here's an interesting stat.

04:43.266 --> 04:48.312
72% of people experience regular bouts with loneliness.

04:49.934 --> 04:50.614
Three out of four.

04:51.876 --> 04:54.098
Look down your row in all of our campuses.

04:55.746 --> 05:00.392
Almost the majority of the folks that are sitting next to you have experienced loneliness, or maybe going through it right now.

05:02.435 --> 05:11.808
I read a story, Chuck Swindall writes a little devotional, and one of the devotions talked about a guy who lived in Kansas, and he decided one day he was gonna place an ad, and it was an unusual ad.

05:12.569 --> 05:22.402
The ad said that for $5, I'll let you call me on the phone, here's my number, and for 30 minutes, you can talk to me and I will not interrupt you for five bucks.

05:23.003 --> 05:25.426
Now it seemed like it's like, why would somebody do that?

05:26.178 --> 05:26.579
But you know what?

05:26.779 --> 05:28.722
He was getting 20 to 30 calls a day.

05:30.345 --> 05:30.606
Why?

05:31.607 --> 05:34.332
People are lonely.

05:34.352 --> 05:35.634
People just want somebody to talk to.

05:36.796 --> 05:39.381
People just want somebody to connect with.

05:41.565 --> 05:42.647
So how do we deal with loneliness?

05:43.308 --> 05:45.011
I put some panic rooms there in your outline.

05:45.231 --> 05:47.154
Here's some typical ways we tend to deal with it.

05:47.355 --> 05:48.877
We run to the panic room of work.

05:48.897 --> 05:51.602
I'm going to work a ton of hours so I don't have to go home to an empty house.

05:53.090 --> 05:54.513
Or we run to the panic room of sex.

05:54.553 --> 05:59.361
I'll just sleep with anybody that was interested in me because it's better to, at least I'm with somebody for a little while.

06:00.884 --> 06:05.152
Or we run to the panic room of support groups, hobbies, sports, dating, social media.

06:07.055 --> 06:09.019
Things we run to that are just temporary fixes.

06:10.141 --> 06:10.943
But do they really help?

06:12.746 --> 06:17.234
I talked to some of the other day, he said, I'm so lonely, I finish Netflix.

06:23.234 --> 06:24.115
Wow, really?

06:24.135 --> 06:24.996
You finished Netflix?

06:25.998 --> 06:27.199
Like a show on Netflix?

06:27.279 --> 06:28.802
No, I finished Netflix.

06:33.007 --> 06:33.948
Loneliness is so common.

06:35.491 --> 06:36.973
It's so well hidden sometimes, you know?

06:38.374 --> 06:39.776
Sam, what are we supposed to do about these feelings?

06:39.796 --> 06:42.320
I've written three types of loneliness down, and they're in your outline.

06:42.340 --> 06:43.461
I want to encourage you to write them in.

06:43.862 --> 06:45.925
Three ways that we get lonely and how to deal with them.

06:45.945 --> 06:49.970
Number one, the first type of loneliness, I believe, is intentional loneliness.

06:50.466 --> 06:51.528
Intentional loneliness.

06:51.728 --> 06:53.931
This is loneliness because I choose to be lonely.

06:55.133 --> 06:56.855
You've hurt me so I'm gonna push you away.

06:58.678 --> 07:00.441
You bother me, I'm never gonna trust again.

07:00.481 --> 07:02.524
You broke up with me, I don't want anything to do with people.

07:03.365 --> 07:04.607
And we isolate ourselves.

07:06.490 --> 07:07.892
And we cause our own loneliness.

07:09.554 --> 07:11.898
There's a quote there in your outline on a lot of people believe this.

07:12.839 --> 07:15.923
Sometimes it's better to be alone because nobody can hurt you.

07:17.726 --> 07:18.788
A lot of us live like that.

07:19.689 --> 07:20.370
Is it true?

07:21.122 --> 07:21.743
I don't think so.

07:23.044 --> 07:26.948
But a lot of us live with that truth, or we think is a truth.

07:27.209 --> 07:28.310
In fact, look at this pattern.

07:28.330 --> 07:29.331
I wrote it there in your outline.

07:29.491 --> 07:30.993
A lot of us fall into pain in life.

07:31.033 --> 07:31.774
And what do we become?

07:31.994 --> 07:32.815
We become the victim.

07:33.696 --> 07:34.176
Poor me.

07:34.437 --> 07:35.057
They hurt me.

07:35.398 --> 07:35.978
I'm broken.

07:36.399 --> 07:38.741
And then what happens when it goes right into the feeling of loneliness?

07:38.901 --> 07:39.903
I feel all alone.

07:42.726 --> 07:44.988
And that feeling of loneliness leads to please fill this in.

07:45.949 --> 07:46.530
Isolation.

07:47.791 --> 07:49.073
We self-isolate.

07:49.133 --> 07:50.354
We withdraw.

07:50.562 --> 07:51.503
from the people around us.

07:52.704 --> 07:56.368
And it may not be physically, we may still be around them, but we withdraw emotionally from them.

07:57.089 --> 07:58.430
We disconnect from them.

07:58.510 --> 08:00.812
It is self-inflicted loneliness.

08:02.074 --> 08:04.896
And a lot of us deal with life that way and pain that way.

08:04.917 --> 08:07.659
The Bible talks about this type of person in Proverbs 18.1.

08:08.640 --> 08:09.781
The wisdom writer writes this.

08:10.362 --> 08:12.464
One who isolates himself pursues what?

08:14.246 --> 08:15.447
Let's say it like we mean it, okay?

08:15.687 --> 08:18.290
One who isolates himself pursues selfish what?

08:18.658 --> 08:26.267
desire, selfish desires, when we get hurt and we isolate ourselves, we become selfish.

08:28.029 --> 08:28.790
And it goes on.

08:29.551 --> 08:32.214
He or she rebels against all sound judgments.

08:32.234 --> 08:37.801
So not only do we get selfish when we pull away, we start making bad choices.

08:39.323 --> 08:40.364
The world is against me.

08:41.645 --> 08:43.608
Bring on a pint of Ben and Jerry's.

08:44.909 --> 08:45.650
Bad choice.

08:46.530 --> 08:49.314
I want to hug my 27 cats and not talk to anybody.

08:50.876 --> 08:51.617
We make bad call.

08:51.797 --> 08:55.822
Or one night stands aren't bad, at least I'm valuable for a couple of hours.

08:57.364 --> 09:00.668
We start making those selfish, bad decisions.

09:01.830 --> 09:02.871
Just because we're lonely.

09:04.934 --> 09:06.736
Proverb says we can't live like that.

09:09.099 --> 09:10.260
Maybe it's more serious than that.

09:11.202 --> 09:14.706
And I want to push pause on the lesson just for a second, and I want to talk to you about something that

09:15.234 --> 09:16.195
is near and dear to my heart.

09:16.215 --> 09:19.340
As a pastor, I talk to a lot of people who are struggling with this type of loneliness.

09:19.860 --> 09:21.903
They've pushed everybody away because they don't want to get hurt again.

09:23.065 --> 09:27.150
And over time, it's gotten worse, and it's gotten worse, and it's gotten worse, and they've contemplated suicide.

09:28.572 --> 09:35.221
First of all, if that's you today at any one of our campuses, I want to tell you that don't you ever, ever give up on yourself.

09:36.643 --> 09:36.823
Ever.

09:37.825 --> 09:39.427
There is someone that wants to help.

09:39.447 --> 09:41.650
In fact, I put a number here on the screens.

09:41.762 --> 09:45.606
jot this down because you may not be dealing with suicide, but you may know somebody who is.

09:47.848 --> 09:49.430
This is the suicide prevention hotline.

09:51.132 --> 09:55.156
There are so many who have isolated themselves so long, they feel like it's never gonna get better.

09:55.596 --> 10:02.223
And they put a permanent solution to a temporary problem by tragically taking their own life.

10:02.243 --> 10:03.684
If this is you today, write this down.

10:03.724 --> 10:06.467
If you know somebody who could use this, write this down, there's help.

10:08.109 --> 10:09.330
There's help, there's always hope.

10:10.882 --> 10:11.643
All right, let's unpause.

10:13.265 --> 10:22.278
Now, this idea of isolation, this self-imposed isolation, there are two words, I put them there in your outline, that push us further into the hole.

10:22.598 --> 10:25.482
If you would write these down, two words that will keep you lonely forever.

10:25.522 --> 10:28.045
Everybody and nobody.

10:29.708 --> 10:30.609
Everybody hates me.

10:31.710 --> 10:32.652
Nobody loves me.

10:33.152 --> 10:34.234
Everybody's out to get me.

10:34.314 --> 10:35.415
Nobody knows I exist.

10:35.435 --> 10:36.237
That's not true.

10:38.880 --> 10:40.242
The world's not out to get you.

10:41.762 --> 10:42.683
Stop pushing it away.

10:44.224 --> 10:45.325
Everybody doesn't hate you.

10:46.166 --> 10:47.668
Now I know it may feel like it, doesn't it?

10:47.888 --> 10:48.649
From time to time?

10:49.730 --> 10:51.511
I don't need them, they're gonna hurt me.

10:53.774 --> 10:59.479
Everybody and nobody, gross generalizations will cause you to feel lonely for a long time.

10:59.519 --> 11:02.282
So what do we do with this self-inflicted loneliness?

11:02.342 --> 11:05.645
James says it the best in James chapter one, verses two through three.

11:05.685 --> 11:10.009
Now I wanna warn you, when I read this two, you're gonna go, not sure, okay?

11:10.029 --> 11:10.610
So let's read it.

11:11.522 --> 11:19.150
Dear brothers and sisters, James says, when troubles of any kind come your way, consider it what?

11:19.371 --> 11:21.273
An opportunity for great what?

11:22.554 --> 11:23.015
Joy.

11:26.779 --> 11:30.243
For you know that when your faith is tested, your endurance will grow.

11:32.665 --> 11:35.048
When they hurt you, consider it joy.

11:35.108 --> 11:36.850
Yay.

11:40.930 --> 11:41.992
That's not what I want to do.

11:44.235 --> 11:45.236
I don't need them in my life.

11:46.498 --> 11:48.441
All they do is hurt me.

11:48.481 --> 11:50.644
Why should I consider what they've done to me?

11:52.267 --> 11:52.607
Joy.

11:54.951 --> 11:57.294
I want you to be careful when we read this passage of Scripture.

11:57.615 --> 11:59.838
He doesn't say be joyful because it happened.

12:01.861 --> 12:03.604
He doesn't say be joyful about the rejection.

12:03.624 --> 12:05.046
He doesn't say be joyful about the pain.

12:05.246 --> 12:05.707
What does he say?

12:05.867 --> 12:07.349
Be joyful that you're going through it.

12:07.369 --> 12:07.610
Why?

12:07.630 --> 12:10.514
Because God's going to use that pain to make you what?

12:10.594 --> 12:11.375
Stronger.

12:13.939 --> 12:14.439
Stronger.

12:15.741 --> 12:17.844
And when we go through pain in our lives, we have to say, you know what?

12:17.864 --> 12:20.328
There's joy in that because God's about to build me up.

12:20.528 --> 12:22.932
God's about to put more strength in me than I had before.

12:23.372 --> 12:24.394
It happened all through Scripture.

12:25.015 --> 12:27.118
Paul wrote most of the New Testament.

12:28.760 --> 12:29.601
He was shipwrecked.

12:30.342 --> 12:31.143
They tried to kill him.

12:31.364 --> 12:32.265
They threw him in prison.

12:32.465 --> 12:35.890
And he wrote his greatest passage of joy while he was in prison.

12:37.890 --> 12:39.552
Because he said, you know what, I'm hurting right now.

12:39.773 --> 12:42.336
They've rejected me, but I'm not gonna let that hold me down.

12:43.738 --> 12:46.662
I'm gonna find joy in that because God is building me stronger.

12:46.743 --> 12:47.884
God is making me tougher.

12:48.365 --> 12:52.070
David, same thing, Psalm 13, David, his life's kind of fallen apart.

12:52.771 --> 12:57.878
But instead of rejecting the world, he says, you know what, I consider it joy because God is making me stronger.

12:59.400 --> 13:01.664
Joseph, you've probably heard the story of Joseph.

13:01.984 --> 13:06.130
Joseph had a bunch of brothers that threw him in a well and a hole and left him for dead.

13:06.626 --> 13:10.971
Joseph could have rejected the world, but he didn't.

13:10.991 --> 13:16.017
Joseph used that pain and that rejection to make himself better.

13:17.398 --> 13:22.104
He became one of the most powerful men in all of Egypt because he didn't push people away.

13:22.224 --> 13:23.966
He didn't allow that to define his life.

13:25.327 --> 13:28.671
He didn't create intentional loneliness.

13:28.851 --> 13:30.193
I put another pattern in your notes.

13:31.394 --> 13:33.396
I believe this is the pattern that God has for us to live.

13:33.737 --> 13:34.898
We need to take the pain

13:35.042 --> 13:38.586
that we're experiencing, the rejection, the hurt, and pray about it.

13:40.288 --> 13:44.532
If you feel rejected, you've been pushed aside or you're hurting, turn to God.

13:44.552 --> 13:46.154
God, what do you want me to learn from this?

13:48.697 --> 13:49.818
And God's gonna answer that prayer.

13:49.838 --> 13:50.859
He's gonna give you a perspective.

13:51.039 --> 13:54.103
He's gonna say, the reason that you're hurting so bad is because I'm still working on you.

13:54.143 --> 13:57.406
Did you know that nobody in this room at any of our campuses, you're not done yet.

13:57.426 --> 13:57.887
Did you know that?

13:58.908 --> 13:59.388
You're not done.

14:00.329 --> 14:04.754
God is developing character in you and strengthening you, and every day,

14:05.570 --> 14:10.976
All of it, sometimes the greatest lessons we learn come through the deepest pain.

14:12.938 --> 14:15.360
So ask God, God, what do you want me to learn from this?

14:15.521 --> 14:17.883
It'll give you a new perspective which will lead to that word again.

14:17.943 --> 14:18.884
There it is, joy.

14:19.965 --> 14:22.288
Thank you, God, for allowing me to go through this.

14:22.408 --> 14:27.313
Not because it hurts, but because I know you're about to use the pain to make me stronger.

14:29.255 --> 14:35.442
Not hate the world more, but be stronger, and that leads to growth.

14:36.514 --> 14:37.135
Please fill that in.

14:38.957 --> 14:40.358
That is how we grow.

14:42.420 --> 14:48.727
Not run away from our problems, not push the world away, but consider those challenges joy so that we grow.

14:49.168 --> 14:50.249
I've got good news for you.

14:51.370 --> 14:56.856
The pain you're going through right now, the rejection you're feeling, the loneliness that's in your gut, it will not last forever.

14:57.176 --> 14:58.238
In fact, fill this in if you would.

14:58.538 --> 15:02.242
The pain you're experiencing is a season, not a sentence.

15:03.683 --> 15:04.665
It is temporary.

15:04.705 --> 15:06.066
You will feel better.

15:06.402 --> 15:07.483
Things will improve.

15:07.804 --> 15:09.927
This is not the way it's going to be for the rest of your life.

15:11.449 --> 15:15.675
No matter who you are, no matter how deep the pain is, but I'm telling you, the enemy's gonna try to convince you otherwise.

15:15.955 --> 15:17.277
You will hurt forever.

15:17.317 --> 15:20.261
The world will reject you forever.

15:20.301 --> 15:22.684
You will hate yourself forever.

15:23.225 --> 15:25.969
Church, it is temporary.

15:27.531 --> 15:29.173
It is a season of your life.

15:30.115 --> 15:32.838
Now, I wish I could tell you, hang in there for another three weeks, you're gonna feel better.

15:34.220 --> 15:35.602
I don't know how long it's gonna last.

15:36.450 --> 15:39.514
But I know that God will use it to make you stronger.

15:40.516 --> 15:41.597
Don't push the world away.

15:41.958 --> 15:44.041
Consider it pure joy.

15:46.644 --> 15:49.809
Don't make one lousy ex-boyfriend make you swear off finding a good man.

15:52.252 --> 15:54.435
I mean, I'm taking, but there's others out there that are wonderful.

15:58.361 --> 16:01.605
Don't let the boss who fired you and called you a bunch of names define who you are.

16:04.329 --> 16:04.850
A parent.

16:05.154 --> 16:21.794
that you've never been able to please, don't let them define the way you treat authority, an unreasonable spouse, a challenging friend, these people in your life are building blocks to make you stronger.

16:23.956 --> 16:25.718
And it's a season, not a sentence.

16:25.738 --> 16:28.301
I put this in your notes, please write it down.

16:28.321 --> 16:32.146
Don't withdraw from everybody over the actions of a somebody.

16:33.922 --> 16:37.927
Don't push everybody away because one person didn't treat you right.

16:40.030 --> 16:41.212
Connect, grow.

16:42.814 --> 16:45.278
Don't let your loneliness be self-inflicted.

16:46.860 --> 16:49.804
Here's a second type of loneliness, circumstantial loneliness.

16:50.765 --> 16:52.427
Because I'm lonely because I have to be.

16:54.510 --> 16:55.512
Circumstantial loneliness.

16:56.793 --> 17:00.759
It's kind of loneliness that comes, not something you did, but something that happened to you.

17:01.119 --> 17:03.122
For example, someone that you love passes away.

17:05.058 --> 17:07.901
or a natural disaster like our friends in Houston, Texas.

17:07.961 --> 17:11.105
They're finding themselves lonely in a gym someplace with nothing left.

17:11.806 --> 17:12.827
It's things that happen to you.

17:13.207 --> 17:14.649
It's when their best friend walks away.

17:15.530 --> 17:17.572
Your spouse divorces you and leaves you there.

17:17.752 --> 17:19.174
That's the circumstantial loneliness.

17:19.194 --> 17:19.915
It's happened to you.

17:20.095 --> 17:21.156
What are you supposed to do with that?

17:21.897 --> 17:22.578
How do you handle it?

17:22.718 --> 17:33.650
In fact, F. Scott Fitzgerald in The Great Gatsby writes this quote, the loneliest moment in someone's life is when they're watching their whole world fall apart and all they can do is stare blankly.

17:35.074 --> 17:35.855
He ever felt like that?

17:37.456 --> 17:38.617
Like everything was falling apart.

17:40.419 --> 17:41.280
Why me, God?

17:42.721 --> 17:44.603
Why does it hurt so bad and you feel alone?

17:45.043 --> 17:46.605
King David dealt with this in Psalm 25.

17:48.587 --> 17:50.969
He was, you know, he had everything.

17:50.989 --> 17:53.711
Now he'd made some bad choices if you read through the Scriptures.

17:53.731 --> 17:56.994
He'd made some bad calls early in his run, but he stringed it out.

17:57.015 --> 18:02.480
And everything was going great for King and as you're reading through Scriptures, it starts to fall apart on him.

18:02.900 --> 18:05.042
Not that he caused it, it just started to hurt him.

18:06.850 --> 18:08.492
And look how David reacts.

18:09.953 --> 18:10.734
What did he say to God?

18:10.995 --> 18:13.357
He says, turn to me and be gracious to me.

18:13.557 --> 18:14.438
He's talking to God here.

18:14.639 --> 18:15.760
David said, for I am what?

18:16.240 --> 18:18.343
I am lonely and afflicted.

18:19.864 --> 18:23.088
Relieve the troubles of my heart and free me from my anguish.

18:23.408 --> 18:25.771
David begs God, God, I want to feel better.

18:25.851 --> 18:26.411
Please help me.

18:28.934 --> 18:30.356
Why don't we do that more?

18:31.217 --> 18:31.998
What do we tend to do?

18:32.018 --> 18:33.920
I put two ideas down in your outline.

18:33.940 --> 18:36.082
Number one, we start second guessing ourselves.

18:36.802 --> 18:38.143
We start second-guessing ourselves.

18:38.343 --> 18:41.046
If I would have just this, something else knew would have happened.

18:41.206 --> 18:44.369
If I'd have just got a second opinion, my husband would still be alive.

18:45.350 --> 18:48.053
If I'd have just gone to marriage counseling, I could have saved my marriage.

18:48.373 --> 18:52.977
If I'd have just been a better friend, then what happens is we play these scenarios out in our mind over and over and over.

18:53.218 --> 18:56.581
If I would have just, if I would have just, if I would have just, you know the problem with that?

18:56.621 --> 19:00.525
It just adds stress.

19:02.727 --> 19:06.130
Because here's the fact, we don't know what would have happened if something would have been different.

19:08.290 --> 19:15.597
We don't know, but yet we waste so much energy second-guessing ourselves, and we become lonelier in the process.

19:16.378 --> 19:17.759
Second thing we do is we blame them.

19:19.100 --> 19:21.082
If they'd have just listened to me, we'd still be a couple.

19:22.404 --> 19:24.666
If they would have just taken better care of themselves, they'd still be alive.

19:24.686 --> 19:25.507
And we get angry.

19:26.127 --> 19:29.731
If they would have just been different, we don't go to God with our problems, we blame them.

19:29.791 --> 19:33.214
If they would have just listened, we wouldn't be divorced.

19:35.476 --> 19:37.298
And then anger gets involved in the mix.

19:37.410 --> 19:43.419
So we feel lonely and angry now and guilty because we've probably blamed ourself at the same time.

19:44.541 --> 19:50.850
And all those emotions, they just drive us further away and that circumstantial loneliness lasts.

19:52.413 --> 19:53.635
So I think we have a choice to make.

19:54.055 --> 20:03.730
When things happen to you and you become lonely, not because of something you did, but because something happened to you, you can either focus on the loss

20:05.154 --> 20:10.963
Or you can look back at that situation and try to find the good in it and put that good in your life.

20:11.063 --> 20:12.845
For example, someone you love passes away.

20:14.408 --> 20:15.249
Look back at their life.

20:16.911 --> 20:17.733
What made them great?

20:17.773 --> 20:18.954
Put those things in your own life.

20:19.675 --> 20:23.822
You can focus on the fact that they're not here, or you can focus on and celebrate the fact that they lived.

20:25.324 --> 20:27.127
The marriage didn't work out the way I thought it would.

20:27.167 --> 20:27.808
Well, you know what?

20:28.068 --> 20:30.391
It might not have worked out, but hey, there were good times.

20:30.451 --> 20:31.193
What were those like?

20:33.756 --> 20:34.898
What did I learn from that marriage?

20:36.674 --> 20:38.417
How did it make me better?

20:39.098 --> 20:39.999
I put in your notes this way.

20:40.259 --> 20:43.264
Choose to focus on the impact, not the absence.

20:44.285 --> 20:48.131
Focus on the impact they made, not the absence of what is here now.

20:48.992 --> 20:50.515
It's a matter of perspective.

20:51.877 --> 20:58.567
Now I'm gonna read you another passage of scripture that I believe will help here, but again, every bit of you is gonna wanna fight against it, because I did when I wrote it.

20:58.727 --> 21:00.509
I didn't write the verse when I copied into my notes.

21:00.550 --> 21:01.451
This is not my writing.

21:01.872 --> 21:02.512
Romans 8, 28.

21:02.553 --> 21:06.258
It says, and we know that God causes some things to work together

21:06.370 --> 21:06.630
No.

21:08.012 --> 21:10.274
We know that God causes most things to work together.

21:10.515 --> 21:10.715
No.

21:11.456 --> 21:11.956
Everything.

21:12.237 --> 21:13.058
Underline it, please.

21:13.138 --> 21:13.618
Circle it.

21:13.658 --> 21:14.119
Star it.

21:14.319 --> 21:16.722
Highlight it.

21:16.742 --> 21:24.390
God causes everything to work together for the good of those who love God and are called according to His purpose for them.

21:27.514 --> 21:28.135
I know it hurts.

21:30.297 --> 21:33.941
It hurts that they're gone.

21:33.961 --> 21:34.802
You didn't cause it.

21:35.970 --> 21:36.872
But you have to deal with it.

21:39.376 --> 21:40.178
And I also know this.

21:42.582 --> 21:45.788
This verse is as true for that situation as it is for anything else.

21:48.253 --> 21:54.605
God will use this loss in your life eventually for good.

21:56.428 --> 21:57.490
Now, I don't know what that looks like.

21:58.370 --> 22:00.132
Maybe it's gonna cause you to draw closer to Him.

22:00.152 --> 22:02.055
Maybe it's gonna be somewhere down the road.

22:02.075 --> 22:04.879
You're gonna be able to help somebody else that's going through a crisis.

22:04.919 --> 22:09.025
And I don't know what it looks like, but God will use this loss in your life.

22:10.787 --> 22:12.670
First of all, to make you stronger like we talked about.

22:12.730 --> 22:14.152
But secondly, He will use it for good.

22:15.794 --> 22:17.857
Everything for good.

22:18.518 --> 22:20.580
That's a promise and God does not break His promises.

22:20.981 --> 22:23.064
Things will get better.

22:24.766 --> 22:25.507
But we have to choose.

22:25.527 --> 22:27.570
Do I wanna focus on the fact that I've lost something?

22:28.258 --> 22:30.101
Or do I want to focus on the fact that it happened?

22:30.962 --> 22:32.023
That I had good times.

22:32.684 --> 22:36.890
There was good in that situation at one time, and put that in my life.

22:38.993 --> 22:40.856
It's one final type of loneliness, and we're done.

22:42.398 --> 22:43.660
It's spiritual loneliness.

22:45.382 --> 22:47.445
I'm lonely because God doesn't care about me.

22:49.087 --> 22:51.651
We had intentional loneliness, which is loneliness I've caused myself.

22:51.891 --> 22:54.275
We had circumstantial loneliness, which is what has happened to me.

22:54.515 --> 22:55.556
This is spiritual loneliness.

22:55.697 --> 22:56.658
You ever felt like that?

22:56.962 --> 22:58.624
Never wondered, God, where are you?

22:58.685 --> 23:02.871
Why do I feel like I'm all alone?

23:02.911 --> 23:04.533
Like I'm some type of spiritual orphan.

23:05.615 --> 23:06.256
Where did you go?

23:06.276 --> 23:09.440
God, do you even exist?

23:10.943 --> 23:11.884
You say you're so loving.

23:12.084 --> 23:12.845
What happened here?

23:14.848 --> 23:15.770
I felt like that before.

23:19.075 --> 23:19.495
Recently.

23:22.860 --> 23:26.866
In times of my life where I've wondered, does God even care about me anymore?

23:28.546 --> 23:29.707
I'm not saying that figuratively.

23:29.727 --> 23:30.388
I mean, literally.

23:30.709 --> 23:32.070
Recently, I've asked that question.

23:33.732 --> 23:35.855
Does God care about me?

23:37.717 --> 23:38.899
Have you ever asked that question before?

23:42.683 --> 23:44.506
My wife and I tried to get pregnant for five years.

23:46.148 --> 23:46.548
No baby.

23:48.150 --> 23:49.552
Watching everybody else have babies.

23:51.334 --> 23:51.915
God, do you care?

23:53.857 --> 23:54.798
God, please heal my dad.

23:56.941 --> 23:57.682
Didn't do that either.

24:01.282 --> 24:03.945
God, we took my daughter into the hospital for a checkup.

24:03.965 --> 24:04.506
She had the flu.

24:05.226 --> 24:06.067
Turned out not to be the flu.

24:06.087 --> 24:07.609
It turned out to be something attacking her heart.

24:09.451 --> 24:10.012
God, where'd you go?

24:12.234 --> 24:14.256
Four months ago, I found my mom passed away in her home.

24:16.139 --> 24:16.979
And I walked out the door.

24:18.641 --> 24:19.442
And I said, God, really?

24:21.665 --> 24:22.406
Do you not care?

24:25.229 --> 24:25.949
Where did you go?

24:25.969 --> 24:30.034
I mean, goodness gracious, God, I'm a pastor.

24:31.234 --> 24:33.317
I serve at the church, I tithe.

24:33.337 --> 24:37.464
I spend all this time, God, praising you, and what happened is you dropped the ball.

24:37.705 --> 24:40.149
Time and time and time and time again.

24:40.409 --> 24:41.110
Where did you go?

24:41.150 --> 24:45.718
You ever felt like that?

24:46.439 --> 24:51.207
Now you may never say it out loud, but you've been praying for something for a long time.

24:51.267 --> 24:52.369
Where the heck is God?

24:54.292 --> 24:57.177
You get angry.

24:57.197 --> 24:57.938
God must not care.

25:00.994 --> 25:05.641
So I stand in front of you and I tell you those things because I no longer feel that way.

25:07.023 --> 25:11.109
And there are two truths and two scriptures that God gave me that brought me, put me right back on the track.

25:11.349 --> 25:12.431
I pray they do the same for you.

25:12.611 --> 25:14.734
If you've ever felt this way before, here's the first truth.

25:14.954 --> 25:15.776
Please write this in.

25:20.182 --> 25:26.091
First truth is that you matter to God.

25:26.111 --> 25:28.274
You matter to God.

25:30.178 --> 25:33.622
You know how I handled that spiritual crisis in my life a few months ago?

25:34.724 --> 25:35.485
I did what you guys do.

25:35.525 --> 25:38.389
I smiled and said I was fine.

25:38.409 --> 25:41.573
And most people, 99% of them went, oh great, good pastor, yay.

25:42.754 --> 25:43.435
How strong you are.

25:46.079 --> 25:49.884
That wasn't fine.

25:49.904 --> 25:56.212
God reminded me in this next passage of scripture that when I was doing my quiet time, I never stopped that, but he gave me this verse.

25:56.272 --> 25:57.874
And if you're feeling like I felt,

25:59.682 --> 26:01.144
I want you to hear this, you matter to God.

26:01.504 --> 26:05.369
Yet Jerusalem says, the people, they said, God has deserted us.

26:06.290 --> 26:07.511
The Lord has forgotten us.

26:07.531 --> 26:09.153
And look what God says back to his people.

26:09.494 --> 26:09.734
Never.

26:11.116 --> 26:12.878
Can a mother forget her nursing child?

26:13.078 --> 26:15.201
Can she feel no love for the child she has born?

26:15.421 --> 26:18.004
But even if that were possible, look, underline his next phrase.

26:18.324 --> 26:20.166
God says, I would not forget you.

26:20.947 --> 26:22.469
See, I have written your name where?

26:22.689 --> 26:24.051
On the palms of my hands.

26:25.793 --> 26:26.514
Your name.

26:27.298 --> 26:31.984
All the campuses, your name, online, everybody here today, your name.

26:33.807 --> 26:34.888
It's on the palm of God's hand.

26:37.472 --> 26:44.721
And when I read that passage of Scripture, I just broke down in tears and I said, God, I don't understand it, but I know that it's true.

26:46.443 --> 26:49.688
Can you imagine when God looks down at His hands and says, it sees your name written there?

26:49.948 --> 26:50.709
That's my girl.

26:53.633 --> 26:54.354
That's my boy.

26:57.346 --> 27:01.090
You matter to God.

27:01.110 --> 27:03.913
You matter to Him.

27:03.933 --> 27:06.775
That broken heart that you have, that loneliness that you feel, it matters.

27:09.038 --> 27:11.000
You try your hardest to fit in and you feel rejected.

27:12.141 --> 27:15.084
You matter to God.

27:15.104 --> 27:16.565
You feel like you're going to be single forever?

27:18.267 --> 27:18.768
That matters.

27:18.848 --> 27:19.869
God cares about that.

27:21.550 --> 27:25.234
You and I matter to God.

27:26.594 --> 27:29.217
And you know, there's one thing I learned going through this spiritual crisis.

27:31.119 --> 27:32.901
God was working in ways I didn't see it.

27:34.824 --> 27:36.045
I thought God had abandoned me.

27:36.085 --> 27:38.688
He hadn't, not only had he not abandoned me, I mattered to him.

27:39.109 --> 27:41.632
And he was already hard at work on other things I didn't see.

27:41.652 --> 27:43.254
He was changing hearts, he was making things better.

27:43.494 --> 27:44.034
I didn't see it.

27:44.054 --> 27:45.496
I was so impatient and so mad.

27:47.018 --> 27:48.960
But God was working everything out for my good.

27:51.363 --> 27:52.004
I mattered to him.

27:52.765 --> 27:53.906
And here's the second truth.

27:55.202 --> 27:56.704
God is never far away.

28:01.149 --> 28:02.912
There's a passage scripture in Matthew 14.

28:04.874 --> 28:11.683
Jesus has fed 5,000 people, more than 5,000 people with two loaves and some fish and all that, and you've read that story before.

28:11.703 --> 28:12.824
He goes up into the hills to pray.

28:14.546 --> 28:17.490
And while he does so, he tells his disciples to get into a boat.

28:17.986 --> 28:19.748
and they go across into this body of water.

28:19.808 --> 28:25.775
And as they're doing so, you know, the storm comes up, maybe you've read the story before, and the guys are getting afraid, the boats swaying, the waves are high.

28:26.016 --> 28:28.499
And of course, you know, Jesus just says, I'm gonna go check on my boys.

28:29.300 --> 28:34.105
So the Bible tells us about three in the morning, he leaves where he was praying, and he walks out under the water, out to the guys.

28:34.145 --> 28:36.809
And of course, Jesus didn't walk on the shore and wave his hands.

28:36.849 --> 28:37.369
Where did he do?

28:37.550 --> 28:39.992
He walked right on the water, right out to the boat.

28:40.173 --> 28:43.276
And the guys are looking out there like, is that a man walking out there?

28:43.296 --> 28:46.340
I mean, the storms are raging, and they can't really see, and the water is flowing.

28:46.560 --> 28:47.922
And they say, who is,

28:48.002 --> 28:48.723
Is that Jesus?

28:49.985 --> 28:50.926
And they thought it was a ghost.

28:51.788 --> 28:53.330
They thought Jesus was a ghost.

28:53.350 --> 28:56.975
And Peter, of course, Peter is the loudest, the most brash one of them all.

28:57.096 --> 28:58.137
What does Peter tell Jesus?

28:58.157 --> 28:58.558
Let's read it.

28:59.219 --> 29:01.262
It's in Matthew 14 starting in verse 28.

29:01.422 --> 29:05.969
Then Peter called to him, Lord, if it's really you, tell me to come to you walking on the water.

29:07.050 --> 29:08.052
Jesus says, yes, come.

29:09.274 --> 29:12.018
So Peter went over the side of the boat and walked on the water to Jesus.

29:12.819 --> 29:15.343
But when he saw the strong wind in the waves, he was what?

29:16.064 --> 29:17.586
Terrified, like you and I would be.

29:18.370 --> 29:19.331
The way I'm gonna drown.

29:19.812 --> 29:20.733
And he began to sink.

29:21.474 --> 29:22.735
Save me, Lord, he shouted.

29:23.036 --> 29:25.118
Jesus immediately reached out and grabbed him.

29:25.378 --> 29:29.483
Please circle the most important word in that entire passage of scripture immediately.

29:31.185 --> 29:32.727
Jesus didn't have to run and catch Peter.

29:32.928 --> 29:33.528
Oh, I got you.

29:33.989 --> 29:35.971
He'd have to pull him out from under the surface of the water.

29:36.011 --> 29:38.975
The Bible says that when Peter cried out, Lord, save me, what happened?

29:39.215 --> 29:40.937
Immediately, Jesus grabbed his arm.

29:43.080 --> 29:43.721
He was right there.

29:47.285 --> 29:48.306
Have you ever doubt

29:50.146 --> 29:51.688
that God isn't around you all the time.

29:51.948 --> 29:53.350
Go back to this passage of scripture.

29:54.391 --> 29:56.574
Jesus was one arm's length away.

29:59.017 --> 30:00.198
All Peter had to say was what?

30:00.258 --> 30:03.422
Save me, Lord.

30:03.442 --> 30:04.704
They've left me and I'm hurting.

30:06.466 --> 30:07.447
I don't fit in anymore.

30:09.129 --> 30:10.631
I lost my best friend to cancer.

30:11.773 --> 30:12.934
My marriage is on the rocks.

30:12.994 --> 30:16.358
Whatever it is in your life, save me, Lord.

30:18.261 --> 30:19.442
I need you, Lord.

30:20.514 --> 30:22.137
I can't do this on my own Lord.

30:22.738 --> 30:24.000
I can't stay afloat on my own.

30:24.300 --> 30:25.282
I want you to fill this in now.

30:25.362 --> 30:28.647
It's the last couple of blanks and I know the tendency is going to be putting those notes away.

30:28.687 --> 30:29.488
Hold on to them, please.

30:31.171 --> 30:39.384
God will never leave your side and his grip is stronger than the waves.

30:41.948 --> 30:43.090
Man, I learned this lesson.

30:45.378 --> 30:55.533
You ever walk through a store and you have a kid with you, one of your children with you and they have a hold of their hand and they want to go to the toy section and they start pulling away wanting to run, do you let them run away to the toy section?

30:57.036 --> 30:57.236
No.

30:58.778 --> 30:59.159
Why not?

31:00.320 --> 31:01.222
Because you want to protect them.

31:02.624 --> 31:04.246
So you grab a hold of that hand and what do you do?

31:04.286 --> 31:05.228
You hold it tighter.

31:08.192 --> 31:08.793
Because you care.

31:08.873 --> 31:14.642
If you're struggling with loneliness today, I don't know if the loneliness is self-inflicted,

31:14.882 --> 31:18.726
I don't know if the loneliness is circumstantial, or I don't know if you've just said, you know what, God, where did you go?

31:22.009 --> 31:23.351
Jesus is right there.

31:25.813 --> 31:29.477
And his grip is stronger than the problems we face.

31:33.361 --> 31:34.602
I want to end today a little differently.

31:37.185 --> 31:40.108
I'm going to ask in just a few minutes, we're going to bow our heads and close our eyes.

31:41.009 --> 31:42.130
Not right now, just in a second.

31:43.778 --> 31:59.578
And I sense today, not only here, but all of our campuses, that there's someone here that's lonely, that there's someone here that needs to be reminded that they matter, that there's someone here that needs to know that Jesus is never gonna leave them, he's never gonna forsake them, and that his grip is strong enough to keep you from harm.

32:02.241 --> 32:04.163
We're gonna pray together, because I wanna pray for you.

32:06.686 --> 32:12.914
I'd be honored to remind you of what God reminded me of not very long ago, that he's there.

32:13.858 --> 32:15.761
So let's all bow our heads, all of our campuses.

32:16.402 --> 32:17.684
Nobody's looking around the room.

32:18.805 --> 32:20.328
All eyes are closed and we're focused.

32:22.591 --> 32:24.754
And I'm gonna ask you to do something a little out of the ordinary.

32:26.337 --> 32:29.622
If you need prayer in this area, you're feeling lonely and you need to reach out.

32:30.162 --> 32:33.748
I wanna encourage you to just reach your hand up in the air and grab ahold of Jesus' hand.

32:34.349 --> 32:37.834
Just reach it up there as hands coming up all over the auditorium.

32:37.854 --> 32:38.595
He's right there.

32:41.419 --> 32:42.100
Let's pray together.

32:42.461 --> 32:43.282
Keep those hands up.

32:43.906 --> 32:45.027
God, I reach out for you.

32:46.469 --> 32:47.210
God, I'm hurting.

32:47.971 --> 32:48.832
God, I feel lonely.

32:48.872 --> 32:58.805
Nobody understands me, God, but you promise in your word that you're never gonna let me go, but you're gonna grab ahold of that hand, Father, and rescue me.

32:59.886 --> 33:04.011
God, I pray for each and every hand up in this auditorium at all of our campuses worldwide, Father.

33:04.251 --> 33:06.774
I pray that Father, you would restore a sense of peace.

33:07.215 --> 33:12.882
Remind them that they matter, remind them that you care, remind them that you love them, and you're never gonna leave them, no matter what.

33:14.146 --> 33:21.734
And we're gonna give you God the glory for the rescue.

33:21.755 --> 33:23.316
Father, give us strength.

33:24.217 --> 33:25.999
Help us draw closer to you.

33:27.641 --> 33:31.806
We love you, we praise you, and we give you all the glory.

33:33.388 --> 33:35.470
In Jesus' name I pray, you put your hands back down.

33:37.372 --> 33:37.712
Amen.

33:38.814 --> 33:39.274
Amen.

33:39.294 --> 33:41.457
Now I wanna tell you something.

33:41.477 --> 33:42.738
Took a lot of courage to do that.

33:46.530 --> 33:49.694
I will be praying for you this week.

33:49.714 --> 33:52.178
I'll be praying that that loneliness you've dealt with for a long time.

33:53.259 --> 33:57.565
This would give you some fresh perspective.

33:57.585 --> 34:00.690
I look around the room today, at least here in this auditorium, I see a lot of tears.

34:02.752 --> 34:06.798
And I know some of the things I said today, I pray they were helpful to you, but I know that also causes some pain.

34:08.420 --> 34:11.344
But my heart has been from the beginning of this message just to give you hope.

34:13.447 --> 34:15.570
And remind you that the loneliness you're experiencing

34:16.162 --> 34:16.723
will pass.

34:17.644 --> 34:19.947
And here at Potential Church, we want to partner with you.

34:22.010 --> 34:25.275
We have prayer partners up front, every service, to pray for you.

34:26.937 --> 34:35.309
Anytime we love to walk through this with you, this feeling of loneliness, not run to the panic room, but let's lean on each other.

34:37.853 --> 34:40.016
I want to give you one last challenge if I could.

34:41.738 --> 34:44.562
We've been talking in the last few weeks about myglasshouse.com.

34:46.274 --> 34:48.417
and we've been asking you to pick up these invite cards.

34:48.818 --> 34:52.183
This is not a pitch to invite people, but it is, and here's why.

34:52.864 --> 34:57.431
It's not because we were gonna fill the auditorium with hundreds of people, although that's probably going to happen.

34:57.892 --> 35:01.998
It's not because this is an awesome church, even though it is the most amazing place in the world.

35:03.260 --> 35:09.129
We want you to invite people to come because those tears you're crying, someone in your life needs the hope you just got.

35:10.491 --> 35:15.218
Someone needs to hear and come face to face with Jesus, and it just changed your life forever.

35:15.522 --> 35:17.265
And you know them, and you love them.

35:17.645 --> 35:23.454
Be courageous, step into their lives, grab some cards and say, I love you enough to invite you to where I come and get hope.

35:24.796 --> 35:26.158
That's why we invite people.

35:27.019 --> 35:30.625
Not to build a big church, but to heal hearts.

35:32.508 --> 35:33.710
That's the heart of our pastors.

35:34.911 --> 35:36.394
I wanna challenge you to grab some of these.

35:36.694 --> 35:38.196
God's put a name on your heart right now.

35:39.779 --> 35:41.141
They might even have your last name.

35:42.383 --> 35:44.466
Sometimes families are the toughest ones to invite, aren't they?

35:45.506 --> 35:51.152
Be courageous, be loving enough to hand them a card, say join me next week as a kickoff to fall.

35:51.172 --> 35:51.773
Let's pray together.

35:53.294 --> 35:54.015
God, you're amazing.

35:57.839 --> 36:07.950
Father, I pray for those that raised their hand today and for those father that raised their hand inside, they didn't raise it physically, but they felt it that you would help us in our loneliness.

36:09.732 --> 36:15.058
The father you would give us the courage and the strength that get up tomorrow and be new and to be trusting,

36:15.170 --> 36:27.766
and to count on you, Father, and to just pour out and tonight even to feel hope again, to not push people away and reject them, but to let people back in.

36:29.348 --> 36:39.961
And Father, I pray for each and every beating heart in this room that all of our campuses be with their families and heal us.

36:39.981 --> 36:44.306
Help us remember, Father, that we're never truly alone, but we have you.

36:44.770 --> 36:46.132
who love us unconditionally.

36:47.054 --> 36:50.721
You knew how our lives were gonna go, yet you made us anyway for greatness.

36:52.243 --> 36:52.644
Thank you.

36:53.786 --> 37:00.098
We'll give you all the praise and all the glory for the breakthrough that we believe and we know is coming.

37:00.118 --> 37:01.220
It's a Christ name that I pray.

37:01.240 --> 37:01.340
Amen.

37:02.542 --> 37:04.786
Amen, let's give God a hand today if you would.

